        <div class='overview-text'>
            <p>Version 1.5 has marked an important point for Rebirth: Redux, it has stopped merely being a slight expansion on Rebirth 1.53, whereby I am taking on more difficult parts of the game code to address some very long standing balance issues with the vanilla game. The biggest of these is the AI performance on a race weekend.</p>
            <p>The AI have always been extremely weak during races due to their incredibly generalised code (which works for all series with minimal code), which means they very rarely make efficient decisions and will constantly drop time to the player as a result. I have therefore taken this as a challenge to myself to see if I could write more efficient AI logic that was bespoke to the series and tier they were in. In essence, I want them to become formidable opponents where the player needs to use all of their skills and cunning to win.</p>
            <p>Therefore, 1.5 marks the beginning of a series of updates where I attempt to make the AI more efficient, more of a challenge, and (hopefully) more fun to play against. Rebirth: Redux is intended to be a long haul mod, and this is a crucial piece of that puzzle.</p>
            <p>Version 1.5 will have 4 distinct stages:
                <ul>
                    <li>1.5: The initial release of the new AI logic, for Open Wheelers only, along with all other bits and pieces I have worked on in the past million months.</li>
                    <li>1.51: The second release of the new AI logic, which will include Endurance and whatever adjustments Open Wheelers needs.</li>
                    <li>1.52: The third release of the new AI logic, which will be more tidying and hopefully finalisation of this part of the project where Open Wheelers and Endurance are concerned.</li>
                    <li>1.53: A small update with various odds and ends I want to implement before I attack GT, such as variable start times to make maximum use of the day/night cycle.</li>
                </ul>
            <p>Once those are done, I will move onto 1.6, which will <em>finally</em> be the big GT update.</p>
            </p>
